kworth, Northumberland, England":"Warkworth, Northumberland, England","Manor, Yorkshire, England":"Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England"},"en":{"1203–1278":"1203–1278","1199–1250":"1199–1250","1215–Female":"1215–Deceased","1225–1250":"1225–1250","1229–Female":"1229–Deceased","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","1199":"1199","20 December 1215":"20 December 1215","1250":"1250","before 1217":"before 1217","Abt 1229":"about 1229","1229":"1229","Cowal, Argyll, Scotland":"Cowal, Argyll, Scotland","Marston St Lawrence, Northamptonshire, England":"Marston St Lawrence, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England","Warkworth, Banbury, Northamptonshire, England":"Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England","Warkworth, Northumberland, England":"Warkworth, Northumberland, England","Manor, Yorkshire, England":"Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Kyong, Kyong Suk, Young, Chae, Chi Young, Hang, Kil, Rin, Sang Hun, Chang, Chong, Insoo, Kum, Sun Young, Yom, Young Hwan.  Cambodian Kiwan, Oeurn, Phoeun, Pich, Saroeuth, Seung, Sophath, Sophea, Yoeun, Phan, Son.  Indian Shanti, Harendra.","Indian (Uttar Pradesh): Brahmin name, from Sanskrit <i>om</i>, the Hindu sacred and mystic syllable uttered at the beginning of prayers.","Cambodian: written ឱម, corresponding to the exclamation of solemn affirmation, of Sanskrit origin (see 1 above), chanted by Buddhist monks."],"variants":[{"name":"Oum","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heang, Hye, Kam, Kan, Kheng, Khin, Kun, Sang, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"Warkworth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Markwardt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Markwardt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Gerhardt.","North German: occupational name for a frontier guard or the guardian of a fenced-off area (such as a woodland), Middle Low German <i>markward</i>, from <i>mark</i> ‘boundary’ + <i>ward(e)</i> ‘guardian’. In medieval folk stories <i>Markwart</i> occurs as a nickname for a jay; it is possible that this use may have influenced the acquisition of the surname in some cases.","German: from the personal name <i>Markward(t)</i>, composed of the elements <i>mark</i> ‘boundary’ + <i>ward</i> ‘guardian’. Compare   Marquardt  ."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":12,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":21,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":56,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Maud of Warkworth was born in 1203, in Warkworth, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir Roger de Lyons, Snr before 1217, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in 1278, in Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1203–1278":"1203–1278","1199–1250":"1199–1250","1215–Female":"1215–Surnud","1225–1250":"1225–1250","1229–Female":"1229–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","1199":"1199","20 December 1215":"20. detsember 1215","1250":"1250","before 1217":"enne 1217","Abt 1229":"umbes 1229","1229":"1229","Cowal, Argyll, Scotland":"Cowal, Argyll, Scotland","Marston St Lawrence, Northamptonshire, England":"Marston St Lawrence, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England","Warkworth, Banbury, Nort